        <div><p>So, yet again doing anything but writing my thesis, I, for the Nth time, started thinking about my <a href='https://halloumiseason.evdokimovas.com'>film blog</a> and how I want to write enormously more reviews and other interesting stuff and grow a newsletter. I started thinking (again) about available newsletter platforms. I redid my "research", decided I will go with Ghost for that, and yada, yada, yada. At one point I went to Ghost's explore page; not only because I wanted to see some of the themes in action, but also because I like blogs.</p>
<p>Surely, there's an aura around Ghost.io created by those all entrepreneur-creator-make-a-pile-of-money-out-of-nowhere-in-a-day productivity gurus, albeit I way underestimated how many times I'd see either become-rich-meditating type of content or how many AI generated images (or for that matter texts, but I couldn't bring myself to read them to confirm they were AI generated) in bananas I'd scroll through.</p>
<p>That's just sad. The individualistic moods covered under the fake veil of get-rich-quickly promises just make me sad.</p>
<p>Long ago, I came to a decision of not reading, supporting or somehow engaging with anything that has to do with AI â€“ if the author didn't have any respect for me as a reader to write a post, edit it, share their thoughts, think about, then I, as a reader, don't want to show them respect that comes with me reading it. I don't understand why we all collectively started treating "fine enough" as "good" and "to strive for". Why would anyone who can do good do just enough to pass? And more importantly, I don't understand, why I would consume something that is not good and has value (at least of being thoughtfully created), but something that is passible enough and has different number of fingers in every scene and 8257038475236 em dashes and phrases that Chomsky would write instead of "Colorless green ideas sleep furiously"?</p>
